<DIV style="position:absolute;top:821;left:144"><nobr><span class="ft1">Source: IDC, March 2005</span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:892;left:144"><nobr><span class="ft12"><b>By Operating Environment</b></span></nobr></DIV>
<DIV style="position:absolute;top:920;left:144"><nobr><span class="ft7">This  study  represents  IDC's  operating  environment  forecast  for  the  search  and<br>retrieval market through 2009. The revenue forecast for the search and retrieval<br>market, segmented by operating environment, is also shown (refer back to Table 1);<br>revenue for 2004 and 2009 is illustrated in Figure 2. Enterprise search engines are<br>moving toward a standards-based environment, although Windows implementations<br>are still popular. We see growth of J2EE and Linux as platforms. Most vendors are<br>moving toward a service oriented architecture that is XML enabled.  </span></nobr></DIV>
</DIV>
